<br>
To those who say that raids aren't about loot, you're kidding yourself.  Raids are not about sightseeing after you've seen the place a few times.  To say that it's fun to take down a god is true, but after you've been to Fear a half dozen times or so, you keep coming back for loot, be it epic or upgrades.<br>
<br>
Raids are about teamwork and trust, especially Fear raids.  You have to trust someone to volunteer to be death touch ammo.  He has to trust the clerics.  Everyone has to trust the break-in group.  Everyone must work together.  When you have people join a fear raid from outside your guild, they trust you to distribute loot as you set out originally.<br>
<br>
Changing the loot rules during a raid upon realization that some quality loot might drop isn't fair to those who came hoping for a shot at an upgrade, and a lot of people come on these raids for that purpose.  If that was your plan all along, you should have communicated it clearly in the post and before the raid started, not in raid chat after the raid is formed, broken in, and clearing.  If that was an on-the-spot decision, it was needlessly unfair and not well-considered.<br>
<br>
I'm not impressed either by your conduct as reported, or by your responses here.  I'm also not impressed by those who claim that everyone should be happy tagging along with your guild, getting the scraps off the loot table that you don't want, and getting things dangled in front of their eyes only to find that you're keeping them for folks with your guild tag above their heads.  If you want to keep raid loot in guild, say so.  What you did lured people to your raid under false pretenses.  <br>
<br>
